<font color="#FF0000">MYTHS AND RECRUITING EFFORTS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 25  1:05:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I had a laugh just now, as when I was reading Doc Spatz's last entry, I thought it was Cook talking.  Sorry to both of you, but it did bring a smile to my face when I realized my mistake!<br><br>
I'd like to swing this discussion a bit to note a situation which recently came to my attention.  We just last weekend took my oldest son off to college--boy does time go by fast!  But when we got back, one of my wife's co-workers began to take on my wife for our emphasis on college for our kids.  She just had a boy enter the US Navy, and she is convinced that when her kid comes out in six years, he'll have a Master's Degree in Nuclear Engineering!  She actually has those expectations of her son, and is questioning our stupidity in financing our kids college education when all we have to do is get them into the Navy and the education is free.  <br><br>
Of course, I know that this is BS, but my wife actually had to call the Navy recruiter and ask him.  He at first stated that this would not happen, and that the most he'd get was &quot;A little short of an Associates Degree&quot; through the Navy technical school.  Then he asked why she had requested the info, and she told him.  At that point, he became very evasive.<br><br>
So, here's my question:  all these guys out there who didn't make a successful transition from the service to civilian life probably had something in common, and I'm wondering if it was unrealistic expectations fostered upon them by service myths of what they could do on the outside?  I'm also wondering how much alcoholism, and all the behavior surrounding it, which I observed was quite common in the USAF and condoned in the 1960's through mid-1970's contributes to this problem of transitioning to civilian life.  How much does the &quot;warrior mentality&quot; mentioned innumerable times above contribute to unrealistic expectations when transitioning into a civilian life?  Finally, are our Armed Forces still &quot;setting people up&quot; for a fall in the civilian world by recruiting efforts like those mentioned above?<br><br>
I worry about this boy coming out without his &quot;masters degree&quot; and trying to face his Mother, who has spread this nonsense throughout her workplace.
<p><code>-- searac@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


